<div class="body">
    <p class="lead">It usually surfaces in a meeting. Someone puts monthly revenue on the screen, and someone else says "that's not the number I have." Two reports, same metric, same month, two answers. A few minutes get spent comparing screenshots, somebody promises to look into it, and the conversation moves on — slightly more skeptical of every number that follows. If this has happened in your organization more than once, you don't have a one-off glitch. You have a structural condition, and it has a predictable anatomy.</p>
    <p>The first instinct is almost always to suspect the data itself — a broken pipeline, a corrupted table, a bug. That's also the least likely explanation. In practice, when two reports disagree, both numbers are usually <em>correct</em>. Each one faithfully answers the question it was built to answer. The problem is that they were built to answer slightly different questions, and nobody can see the difference from the outside.</p>

    <p class="pull">When two reports disagree, both are usually right — about different questions. The disagreement lives in the definitions, not the data.</p>

    <h2>The five honest reasons reports disagree.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">It's rarely the data itself</span>

    <p><strong>1. Definition drift.</strong> "Revenue" is not one thing. Booked revenue, recognized revenue, invoiced revenue, and collected cash are four different numbers that all answer to the same word. The same goes for "active customer," "churn," and nearly every metric that matters. When the definition lives in people's heads instead of on paper, each team resolves the ambiguity in the way that makes sense for their work — and each resolution is defensible. The numbers diverge because the meanings already had.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Source divergence.</strong> The CRM, the billing system, and the warehouse each hold something called revenue, and they genuinely differ: deals that closed but haven't been invoiced, invoices issued but adjusted later, records that sync on different schedules. Two reports pulling the "same" metric from two systems aren't pulling the same metric at all. Without one agreed authoritative source per metric, every system is a legitimate source — which means none of them is.</p>

    <p><strong>3. Timing and refresh windows.</strong> One report is a snapshot taken at month-end close. The other reads live data and was opened on the 4th, after two late invoices landed and one refund posted. Neither report is stale or wrong — they describe the same business at two different moments. Timing differences are the most innocent cause on this list and the one most often mistaken for an error.</p>

    <p><strong>4. Filter and population differences.</strong> One report excludes test accounts and internal usage. The other doesn't. One counts pilot customers; the other waits until the first paid invoice. These choices are invisible in the final number — nothing on the dashboard says "excludes 14 pilot accounts" — so two careful, well-built reports can disagree by a few percent forever, with both builders certain theirs is right. Because it is.</p>

    <p><strong>5. Grain and counting rules.</strong> Are you counting orders, invoices, or invoice line items? Does a customer with two subsidiaries count once or twice? When a deal is amended, does it replace the original record or sit alongside it? Aggregation rules like these are decided quietly, deep in a query, by whoever built the report — and two reasonable people will decide them differently.</p>

