    <h2>Why it never stays fixed.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">Reconciliation treats the instance, not the cause</span>
    <p>Most organizations handle this the same way: when a mismatch surfaces, an analyst gets assigned to reconcile it. They trace both numbers, find the definitional or timing difference, explain it in an email, and everyone nods. The instance is resolved. The cause is untouched. Nothing was written down, no source was declared authoritative, no report was retired — so the next mismatch is already in production, waiting for its meeting.</p>
    <p>Reconciliation as a recurring activity is one of the most expensive habits in reporting. It consumes skilled analyst time, it resolves nothing permanently, and every public episode of "the numbers don't match" spends a little more of the data team's credibility — a cost that compounds quietly. (We've written about <a href="/insights/hidden-cost-conflicting-kpis">what conflicting metrics actually cost</a>; the reconciliation tax is a large share of it.)</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <h3>What "single source of truth" actually requires</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>One named authoritative source per critical metric — a decision, recorded, not a platform purchase.</li>
        <li>A written definition for each metric: formula, filters, timing, and a named owner.</li>
        <li>A short note on each known legitimate variant — what it includes, when to use it, and what to call it.</li>
        <li>A lightweight change process, so the answer stays settled when systems or teams change.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>The fix is a decision, not a project.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">And it's smaller than it looks</span>
    <p>"Single source of truth" gets talked about as if it requires a data platform migration. It doesn't. It requires somebody with authority to make four small decisions per metric, and a place to write them down. For each critical metric: <strong>name the authoritative source</strong> — the one system the official number comes from, chosen deliberately, with the trade-offs acknowledged. <strong>Write the definition</strong> — formula, filters, timing window, and owner, in plain English, somewhere people actually look. <strong>Reconcile once, properly</strong> — trace the existing variants to their queries, document <em>why</em> they differ, and decide which differences are legitimate. <strong>Retire or relabel the rest</strong> — a report that contradicts the official number either disappears or gets an honest name like "Bookings (CRM view)" so it stops impersonating the canonical figure.</p>
    <p>The technical work in all of this is usually hours, not months. The real work is the conversation — getting the people who own the competing versions to agree on one answer and accept constraint. That's uncomfortable in a way that building another dashboard isn't, which is exactly why the dashboard keeps getting built instead. But the organizations that have this conversation once, and record the outcome, stop having the meeting where two numbers fight.</p>

    <div class="tip">
      <div class="tlabel">Where to start right now</div>
      <p>Take the metric that most recently caused an argument. Trace both numbers back to their queries and write a one-paragraph note: which source, which filters, which timing window, for each. The gap will explain itself — it nearly always does. Then make the call: one of them is the official number from now on, and the other gets renamed or retired. If you want a read on how widespread the problem is beyond that one metric, the free <a href="/resources/#checklist">Reporting Trust Health Check</a> scores your whole environment in about three minutes — no email required.</p>
